{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Application Configuration</h1>
    <p>
        Rhapsody keeps all configuration in the <code>config/</code> directory and the <code>.env</code> file. <strong>You should never modify files inside <code>/core</code>.</strong> This ensures that framework updates won't overwrite your customisations.
    </p>

    <h2>Configuration Files</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><code>.env</code> – environment‑specific variables (database, mail, caching driver, etc.).</li>
        <li><code>config.php</code> – general settings (app version, theme, logging paths).</li>
        <li><code>config/middleware.php</code> – middleware definitions (map and global list).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Adding New Configuration</h3>
    <p>You can create additional config files in the <code>config/</code> folder and load them in your controllers or services as needed:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">$myConfig = require __DIR__ . '/config/my-settings.php';</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Environment Variables (<code>.env</code>)</h2>
    <p>
        The <code>.env</code> file contains sensitive or environment‑specific data. Never commit it to version control. Use <code>.env.example</code> as a template.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">APP_ENV=development
APP_BASE_URL="/rhapsody"
DB_HOST=127.0.0.1
CACHE_DRIVER=file</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>View File Hierarchy & Theme System</h2>
    <p>
        Rhapsody uses Twig for templating. The framework looks for view files in a specific order, making it easy to override core templates or build custom themes.
    </p>

    <h3>Directory Structure</h3>
    <p>The default view directories are:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">views/
├── themes/
│   ├── default/          ← Fallback theme (always available)
│   │   
│   └── my_custom_theme/  ← Your active theme (if set)
│       ├── layouts/
│       └── home/
└── core/                  ← Core framework views (default, but overridable)
    ├── layouts/
    ├── docs/
    └── ...</code></pre>

    <h3>Theme Resolution Order</h3>
    <p>When you render a view (e.g., <code>$this->view('home/index.twig')</code>), the framework searches in this order:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Active theme</strong> – <code>views/themes/{{ APP_THEME }}/</code></li>
        <li><strong>Default theme</strong> – <code>views/themes/default/</code></li>
        <li><strong>Core views</strong> – <code>views/core/</code></li>
    </ol>
    <p>If a template exists in your active theme, it is used. Otherwise, the framework falls back to the default theme, and finally to the core view. The application will throw a fatal error if it cannot find your template in one of the above directories.</p>

    <h3>Setting the Active Theme</h3>
    <p>Define the theme in your <code>.env</code> file:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">APP_THEME=my_custom_theme</code></pre>
    <p>If not set, the default theme is used.</p>

    <h3>Overriding Core Templates</h3>
    <p>To override a core template (e.g., the main layout), simply create a file with the same path inside your active theme. For example, to override <code>views/core/layouts/main.twig</code>, create <code>views/themes/my_custom_theme/layouts/main.twig</code>.</p>
    <p>You can also extend core templates using Twig’s <code>{% extends %}</code> tag with the <code>@core</code> namespace:</p>
    <pre><code>{% extends "@core/layouts/main.twig" %}</code></pre>

    <h3>Custom View Namespaces</h3>
    <p>If you need additional view directories (e.g., for reusable modules), you can add them to the Twig loader in <code>bootstrap.php</code>:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">$loader->addPath(__DIR__ . '/modules/blog/views', 'blog');</code></pre>
    <p>Then render a view using the namespace: <code>$this->view('@blog/index.twig')</code>.</p>

    <h3>Error Pages</h3>
    <p>Custom error pages (404, 500, etc.) can be placed in <code>themes/{{ APP_THEME }}/errors/</code>. The framework will automatically use the theme’s error template if it exists, falling back to the default theme.</p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Middleware Configuration</h2>
    <p>See the <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/middleware">Middleware documentation</a> for details on <code>config/middleware.php</code>.</p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Cache Driver</h2>
    <p>Switch between <code>file</code> and <code>redis</code> drivers in <code>.env</code>:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">CACHE_DRIVER=redis
REDIS_HOST=127.0.0.1
REDIS_PORT=6379</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Logging</h2>
    <p>Configure log paths in <code>config.php</code> under the <code>logging</code> key.</p>

    <hr>
    <div class="bg-blue-100 border-l-4 border-blue-500 text-blue-700 p-4">
        <strong>Golden Rule:</strong> If you need to change behaviour, look for a configuration file first. Only extend or replace classes – never edit core files directly.
    </div>
{% endblock %}